Preliminary cleaning process (note, here it is eval=FALSE for convenience) leading up to group_biom_v3.Rdata:

######## Initial Dataset Creation 

load("tech_data.Rdata") #ABS dataset

dataset = subset(tech_biom, select = c(SABDYMS, BDYMSQ04, EXLWTBC, SEX, BMISC, PHDCMWBC, PHDCMHBC, PHDKGWBC)) #extract initial variables of interest 

dataset$EXLWTBC = as.numeric(as.character(dataset$EXLWTBC)) #fix class type of exercise as it was originally factor

dataset1 = dataset[rowSums(is.na(dataset)) == 0,] #remove all rows with NA values 

dataset1 = dataset1[dataset1$EXLWTBC != 9999, ] #remove placeholder values 
dataset1 = dataset1[dataset1$EXLWTBC != 9996, ] #remove placeholder values 

for (i in 1:nrow(dataset1)) {
  if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1) {
    dataset1$RFM[i] = 64 - (20 * dataset1$PHDCMHBC[i] / dataset1$PHDCMWBC[i])
  } 
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2) {
    dataset1$RFM[i] = 76 - (20 * dataset1$PHDCMHBC[i] / dataset1$PHDCMWBC[i])
  }
} #calculate RFM as needed

for (i in 1:nrow(dataset1)) {
  if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 2) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 1
  } 
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 5) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 2
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 5 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 13) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 3
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 13 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 17) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 4
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 17 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 24) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 5
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 1 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 25) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 6
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 10) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 1
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 10 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 13) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 2
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 13 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 20) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 3
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 20 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 24) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 4
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 24 && dataset1$RFM[i] < 31) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 5
  }
  else if (dataset1$SEX[i] == 2 && dataset1$RFM[i] >= 31) {
    dataset1$RFM_Category[i] = 6
  }
} #calculate RFM categories as needed 

dataset2 = subset(dataset1, dataset1$RFM > 0) #remove RFM<0 since that doesn't make sense (only 2 entries so it's okay regardless)

dataset2$SABDYMS = droplevels(dataset2$SABDYMS) #remove unused levels 
dataset2$BDYMSQ04 = droplevels(dataset2$BDYMSQ04) #remove unused levels 


# recoding levels for intuitiveness and matching analysis
recode = c("Non-Overweight SP" = 1, "Non-Overweight SP" = 2, "Overweight SP" = 3)
dataset2$SABDYMS = factor(dataset2$SABDYMS, levels = recode, labels = names(recode)) 

recode2 = c("Male" = 1, "Female" = 2)
dataset2$SEX = factor(dataset2$SEX, levels = recode2, labels = names(recode2))

recode3 = c("Diet" = 1, "Diet" = 2, "Diet" = 3, "No-Diet" = 5)
dataset2$BDYMSQ04 = factor(dataset2$BDYMSQ04, levels = recode3, labels = names(recode3))

recode4 = c("Non-Obese" = 1, "Non-Obese" = 2, "Non-Obese" = 3, "Non-Obese" = 4, "Non-Obese" = 5, "Obese" = 6)
dataset2$RFM_Category = factor(dataset2$RFM_Category, levels = recode4, labels = names(recode4))
dataset2$RFM_Category = droplevels(as.factor(dataset2$RFM_Category))

# adding on accuracy of self-perception for later analysis (note this isn't used in step 1, only introduced until step 2)
for (i in 1:nrow(dataset2)) {
  if (dataset2$SABDYMS[i] == "Non-Overweight SP" && dataset2$RFM_Category[i] == "Non-Obese") {
    dataset2$`Self-Perception`[i] = "Accurate SP"
  } 
  else if (dataset2$SABDYMS[i] == "Non-Overweight SP" && dataset2$RFM_Category[i] == "Obese") {
    dataset2$`Self-Perception`[i] = "Inaccurate SP"
  }
  else if (dataset2$SABDYMS[i] == "Overweight SP" && dataset2$RFM_Category[i] == "Obese") {
    dataset2$`Self-Perception`[i] = "Accurate SP"
  }
  else if (dataset2$SABDYMS[i] == "Overweight SP" && dataset2$RFM_Category[i] == "Non-Obese") {
    dataset2$`Self-Perception`[i] = "Inaccurate SP"
  }
}
dataset2$`Self-Perception` = as.factor(dataset2$`Self-Perception`) #changing from character to factor

# cleaning up dataset to contain only variables of analysis
dataset3 = subset(dataset2, select=c("Self-Perception", "SABDYMS", "SEX", "BDYMSQ04", "RFM", "PHDKGWBC", "EXLWTBC"))

Aims of Analysis

This STATS report stands as supplementary material underlying the analysis performed in our team’s main report, complete with code, methodology, and figures where applicable. In line with our research question of exploring the influences of accurate/inaccurate self-perception on lifestyle factors, our statistical approach can be summarised into two key stages:

  • Stage 1: Exploring the trends between individuals’ self-perceived weight status and other personal and lifestyle factors.
    • The variable of interest here is self-perceived weight status, or SABDYMS, of which we use various types of models and exploratory analysis to look to evaluate broader relationships as suggested by intuition and literature.
    • Analyses in this stage featured broader and more general evaluation with the main purpose of grasping trends and relationships between variables in order to guide more specific discussion in stage 2.
    • Factor Analysis of Mixed Data (PCA-esque model, which from now, will be termed as PCA for convenience), Basic Logistic Regression, and PCA Logistic Regression was performed in this stage.
  • Stage 2: Exploring personal and lifestyle factor differences and trends between those individuals who perceived their own weight status correctly, and those who perceived their own weight status incorrectly.
    • In this stage, we’ve created a new variable to represent the accurate or inaccurate self-perception of weight, named Self-Perception, which is the variable of interest here.
    • Analyses in this stage is focused on evaluating actual explanatory power of each personal and lifestyle variable with the underlying goal of discovering marked differences that may cause an individual to self-perceive their weight accurately, as opposed to inaccurately.
    • pending models used

Analysis and Methodology

Stage 1

Factor Analysis of Mixed Data

Factor analysis of mixed data (FAMD) was selected as a model due to its accomodation for data that is comprised of both categorical and numerical data. Given that our selected dataset of interest is of such specification, FAMD was deemed appropriate for our purposes. As such, FAMD was performed on the initial variables - noting the removal of Self-Perception accuracy, due to irrelevance in stage 1, and SABDYMS, due to it being the response variable - to gather insights into the general explanatory and discriminatory power of each variable.

PCA_dataset = dataset3
initial_variables = subset(PCA_dataset, select=-c(`Self-Perception`, SABDYMS))
initial_response = PCA_dataset$SABDYMS

res.famd = FAMD(initial_variables, graph=FALSE)
kable(round(get_eig(res.famd),3), caption="Fig 3: Principal component details")

Dim.2 1.284 25.684 61.304
Dim.3 1.004 20.077 81.381
Dim.4 0.813 16.266 97.647
Dim.5 0.118 2.353 100.000 
fviz_screeplot(res.famd, caption="Fig 4: FAMD scree plot")

There are a couple of key notes here:

  • The first three principal components were selected as relevant here due to their combined variance explanation of 81.4%, and how the third principal component - although slightly diminishing - was still deemed important due to its relatively close variance percentage to principal component 2.
  • All our variables appear amongst the top three principal components, however, dietary status BDYMSQ04 is notably less powerful according to FAMD compared to other variables as it fails to exceed 30%.
  • The variance explanation distribution is not majorly dominated by the first principal component, only standing at a 35.6%. This implies a more distributed spread of explanatory power across the components, in our case, the top three components.
fviz_contrib(res.famd, "var", axes = 1, title="Contribution of Variables to First Principal Component", caption="Fig 5: First principal component") # Contribution to the first dimension; gender+rfm = "gender obesity"

fviz_contrib(res.famd, "var", axes = 2, title="Contribution of Variables to Second Principal Component", caption="Fig 6: Second principal component") # Contribution to the second dimension; true weight + diet = "behaviour"

fviz_contrib(res.famd, "var", axes = 3, title="Contribution of Variables to Third Principal Component", caption="Fig 7: Third principal component") # Contribution to the second dimension; exercise + diet = "lifestyle"

  • The identities of these components can be seen above:

    • First principal component (PC1) represents a mixture of gender and relative fat mass.
    • Second principal component (PC2) represents a mixture of true weight and diet.
    • Third principal component (PC3) represents a mixture of exercise and diet.

Standard Logistic Regression

Standard logistic regression was performed here with SABDYMS - self-perceived weight status - as the response variable against the other predictors in the dataset (minus accuracy of self-perception as aforementioned stage 1 irrelevancy). Using a 50-repeat 5-cross-fold validation approach, the results are as follows:

LR_dataset = subset(dataset3, select=-`Self-Perception`)

train_control = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats=50)
logistic_model = train(SABDYMS~(.)^2, data=LR_dataset, trControl=train_control, method="glm", family=binomial())
coefficient_summary = summary(logistic_model)$coefficients
logistic_summary = data.frame("Variable" = rownames(coefficient_summary), "Coefficient" = round(coefficient_summary[,1],3), "Std. Error" = round(coefficient_summary[,2],3), "P-Value" = round(coefficient_summary[,4],3))
rownames(logistic_summary) = NULL
#contrasts(dataset3$SABDYMS) #0 = non-overweight SP, 1 = overweight SP
#logistic_model$results --> accuracy 0.8070316
logistic_summary2 = logistic_summary[order(-abs(logistic_summary$Coefficient)),]

We note that this has been performed with respect to inter-variable coefficients as well, in addition to single variable effects, due to our postulated inter-variable impacts that could affect an individual’s self-perception especially in a system as complex as the human body and lifestyle behaviours.

We further visualise this logistic model in two ways: firstly, we visualise the logistic model with respect to a baseline average RFM; and secondly, we visualise it with respect to a baseline average true weight. This allowed us to extract insights into the probabilistic effects of dietary status and gender on one’s probability of overweight self-perception:

# extracting the coefficients 
constant = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[1]
Non_Diet = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[3]
exercise = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[6]
Female = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[2]
relative_fat_mass = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[4]
true_weight = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[5]
non_diet_exercise = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[13]
non_diet_female = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[7]
non_diet_rfm = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[11]
non_diet_true_weight = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[12]
exercise_female = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[10]
exercise_rfm = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[15]
exercise_true_weight = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[16]
female_rfm = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[8]
female_true_weight = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[9]
rfm_true_weight = logistic_model$finalModel$coefficients[14]


################################ a) true weight, rfm fundamental 
X1_range = seq(from=min(LR_dataset$PHDKGWBC), to=max(LR_dataset$PHDKGWBC), by=.01) #setting up visualisation for true weight axis 
X2_val = mean(LR_dataset$RFM) #setting up baseline average RFM

# calculating probabilities with respect to different dietary and gender combinations
Male_Diet_logits = constant + Non_Diet*0 + exercise + Female*0 + relative_fat_mass*X2_val + true_weight*X1_range +
  non_diet_exercise*0 + non_diet_female*0 + non_diet_rfm*X2_val*0 + non_diet_true_weight*X1_range*0 +
  exercise_female*0 + exercise_rfm*X2_val*1 + exercise_true_weight*X1_range*1 + female_rfm*X2_val*0 + 
  female_true_weight*X1_range*0 + rfm_true_weight*X1_range*X2_val

Female_Diet_logits = constant + Non_Diet*0 + exercise + Female*1 + relative_fat_mass*X2_val + true_weight*X1_range +
  non_diet_exercise*0 + non_diet_female*0 + non_diet_rfm*X2_val*0 + non_diet_true_weight*X1_range*0 +
  exercise_female*1 + exercise_rfm*X2_val*1 + exercise_true_weight*X1_range*1 + female_rfm*X2_val*1 + 
  female_true_weight*X1_range*1 + rfm_true_weight*X1_range*X2_val

Male_Non_Diet_logits = constant + Non_Diet*1 + exercise + Female*0 + relative_fat_mass*X2_val + true_weight*X1_range +
  non_diet_exercise*1 + non_diet_female*0 + non_diet_rfm*X2_val*1 + non_diet_true_weight*X1_range*1 +
  exercise_female*0 + exercise_rfm*X2_val*1 + exercise_true_weight*X1_range*1 + female_rfm*X2_val*0 + 
  female_true_weight*X1_range*0 + rfm_true_weight*X1_range*X2_val

Female_Non_Diet_logits = constant + Non_Diet*1 + exercise + Female*1 + relative_fat_mass*X2_val + true_weight*X1_range +
  non_diet_exercise*1 + non_diet_female*1 + non_diet_rfm*X2_val*1 + non_diet_true_weight*X1_range*1 +
  exercise_female*1 + exercise_rfm*X2_val*1 + exercise_true_weight*X1_range*1 + female_rfm*X2_val*1 + 
  female_true_weight*X1_range*1 + rfm_true_weight*X1_range*X2_val

Male_Diet_probs = exp(Male_Diet_logits)/(1 + exp(Male_Diet_logits))
Female_Diet_probs = exp(Female_Diet_logits)/(1 + exp(Female_Diet_logits))
Male_Non_Diet_probs = exp(Male_Non_Diet_logits)/(1 + exp(Male_Non_Diet_logits))
Female_Non_Diet_probs = exp(Female_Non_Diet_logits)/(1 + exp(Female_Non_Diet_logits))

plot.data = data.frame("Male Diet"=Male_Diet_probs, "Female Diet"=Female_Diet_probs, 
                       "Male Non-Diet"=Male_Non_Diet_probs, "Female Non-Diet"=Female_Non_Diet_probs, X1=X1_range)

group = as.factor(c("Male.Diet", "Female.Diet", "Male.Non.Diet", "Female.Non.Diet"))
plot.data2 = data.frame(pivot_longer(plot.data, group, names_to = "Groups", values_to = c("prob")))
plot.data2$groups = as.factor(plot.data2$Groups)
plot.data2$Groups = factor(plot.data2$Groups, levels = c("Male.Diet", "Female.Diet", "Male.Non.Diet", "Female.Non.Diet"))

ggplot(plot.data2, aes(x=X1, y=prob, color=Groups)) +
  geom_line(lwd=1.5) + theme_bw() + geom_hline(yintercept=c(1/3, 2/3), linetype="dashed", color="red") +

plot.data2$groups = as.factor(plot.data2$Groups)

ggplot(plot.data2, aes(x=X1, y=prob, color=Groups)) +
  geom_line(lwd=1.5) + theme_bw() + geom_hline(yintercept=c(1/3, 2/3), linetype="dashed", color="red") +
  labs(x="RFM", y="Probability of Self-Perceived Overweight", 
       title="Categorical Effects on Self-Perceived Weight Outcomes", 
       subtitle="Average True Weight Level", caption="Fig 14: Logistic regression model with average true weight level")

FAMD/PCA Logistic Regression

Integrating the principal components into a logistic regression, also using 50-repeat 5-cross-fold validation approach, we aimed to evaluate the ability for logistic regression to accurately predict self-perceived overweightness. This would provide additional insights into the apparent strengths of our personal and lifestyle variables in explaining overweight self-perceptions.

PCA_LR_dataset = data.frame("response" = initial_response, "PC1" = PC1.ind, "PC2" = PC2.ind, "PC3" = PC3.ind)
PCA_logistic_model = train(response ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3, data=PCA_LR_dataset, trControl=train_control, method="glm", family=binomial())
#PCA_logistic_model$results --> accuracy is 0.7832372
PCA_coefficient_summary = summary(PCA_logistic_model)$coefficients
PCA_logistic_summary = data.frame("Variable" = rownames(PCA_coefficient_summary), "Coefficient" = round(PCA_coefficient_summary[,1],3), 
                              "Std. Error" = round(PCA_coefficient_summary[,2],3), "P-Value" = round(PCA_coefficient_summary[,4],3))
rownames(PCA_logistic_summary) = NULL

PCA_logistic_summary2 = PCA_logistic_summary[order(-abs(PCA_logistic_summary$Coefficient)),]
kable(PCA_logistic_summary2, caption="Fig 15: Table of coefficients and significance")

Variable Coefficient Std..Error P.Value

1 (Intercept) -0.200 0.030 0
4 PC3 -0.128 0.033 0 
#contrasts(PCA_LR_dataset$response) #0 = non-overweight, 1 = overweight
PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredictedRaw = PCA_logistic_model$finalModel$fitted.values
PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredicted = NA

for (i in 1:nrow(PCA_LR_dataset)) {
  if (PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredictedRaw[i] >= 0.5) {
    PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredicted[i] = "Overweight SP"
  }
  else {
    PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredicted[i] = "Non-Overweight SP"
  }
}

PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy = ifelse(PCA_LR_dataset$response == PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticPredicted, "Accurate", "Inaccurate")
PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy = as.factor(PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy)
PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy = factor(PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy, levels = c("Inaccurate", "Accurate"))
PCA_LR_dataset$alpha = ifelse(PCA_LR_dataset$LogisticAccuracy=="Inaccurate", 1, 0.5)


ggplot(PCA_LR_dataset, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2, colour=LogisticPredicted)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) + theme_bw() + labs(title="PCA Logistic Regression Prediction", caption="Fig 16: Logistic model predictions")

ggplot(PCA_LR_dataset, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2, colour=LogisticAccuracy, alpha=alpha)) + 
  geom_point() + theme_bw() + labs(title="PCA Logistic Regression Misclassification Overview", caption="Fig 17: Logistic model misclassifications") + scale_alpha(guide="none")

So while the PCA logistic model produced quite a generic and fine-line classification model, its actual error is non-negligible with majority of misclassifications occurring near the centre areas of each principal component. This suggests that the model struggles to accurately predict self-perception near the boundary of each principal component - an idea that leads us to stage 2 where we try to identify the nature of these boundaries.

Classification Tree

Due to our variable of interest being qualitative we decided to use “Classification tree” to predict “Self-perception”. Classification Trees used for predicting qualitative variables oppose to Decision Trees also predictor variables could be qualitative and quantitative.

# note that the following sections were performed independently, so some code may repeat in nature
load("group_biom_v3.rdata")
for (i in 1:nrow(dataset3)) {
  if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] < 2) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  } 
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 2 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 5) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 5 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 13) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 13 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 17) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 17 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 24) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Male" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 25) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 1
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] < 10) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 10 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 13) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 13 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 20) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 20 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 24) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 24 && dataset3$RFM[i] < 31) {
    dataset3$RFM_Category[i] = 0
  }
  else if (dataset3$SEX[i] == "Female" && dataset3$RFM[i] >= 31) {

Caret Package: Cross-Validation

We Performed 10 repeated 10-fold Cross-validation to determine Complexity Paremeter that maximizes Accuracy of the Tree prediction.

n_grid <- 100
tuneGrid <- expand.grid(cp = seq(0.01, 0.001, length=n_grid))
res4 <- train(
  SELFPERC ~ .,
  data = train1,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                           number = 10,
                           repeats = 10),
  tuneGrid = tuneGrid)
ggplot(res4) +  theme_bw() + labs(title = "Cross-Validation using Caret", caption = "Fig 25: Cross Validation result graph")

We want the cp value of the smallest tree that has the smallest cross validation error. The CV optimal value of cp is 0.01.

min_val <- which.min(res4$results$Accuracy)
opt_cv  <- res4$results$cp[min_val]


Classification Tree:

Based on the Gini Index the variables that give best split were: RFM, PHDKGWBC (True weight), and SEX.

res5 <- prune.rpart(res2, cp = opt_cv)
split.fun <- function(x, labs, digits, varlen, faclen)
{
    labs   <- sub("PHDKGWBC",   "True Weight", labs)
    labs   <- sub("RFM",      "Relative Fat Mass", labs)
    labs
}
rpart.plot(res5,type=4,extra=1, main="Classification Tree: Accurate vs Inaccurate Self-Perception",cex=0.5, split.fun = split.fun)

  • True Weight less than 70; and Relative Fat Mass (RFM) more than 40 -> inaccurate
  • True Weight less than 85; Relative Fat Mass (RFM) between 24 - 40; and Male -> inaccurate
  • True Weight less than 72; Relative Fat Mass (RFM) between 31 - 40; and Female -> inaccurate
